1 Sec. 795a. (1) An Subject to subsection (10), an electronic
2 voting system shall must not be used in an election unless it that
3 electronic voting system is approved by the board of state
4 canvassers as meeting the requirements of sections 794 and 795 and
5 instructions regarding recounts of ballots cast on that electronic
6 voting system that have been issued by the secretary of state,
7 unless section 797c has been complied with, and unless it that
8 electronic voting system meets 1 of the following conditions:
9 (a) Is certified by an independent testing authority
10 accredited by the national association National Association of
11 state election directors State Election Directors and by the board
12 of state canvassers.
13 (b) In the absence of an accredited independent testing
14 authority, is certified by the manufacturer of the voting system as
15 meeting or exceeding the performance and test standards referenced
16 in subdivision (a) in a manner prescribed by the board of state
17 canvassers.
18 (2) The vendor or representative seeking approval of an
19 electronic voting system shall must do all of the following:
20 (a) Deposit with the secretary of state a nonrefundable
21 application fee of $1,500.00 for a new electronic voting system and
22 a fee of $500.00 for an upgrade to any existing electronic voting
23 system.
24 (b) File with the secretary of state a list of all states in
25 which the electronic voting system has been approved for use. This
26 list shall must state how long the electronic voting system has
27 been used in the state and shall must disclose any reports compiled
28 by any state or local government concerning the performance of the
29 electronic voting system. The vendor shall remain remains
STM H02463'25 (H-1) m2t81w

6
1 responsible for filing this information on an ongoing basis.
2 (c) File with the secretary of state copies of all standard
3 contracts and maintenance agreements used in connection with the
4 sale of the electronic voting system. All changes to standard
5 contracts and maintenance agreements shall must be filed with the
6 secretary of state.
7 (d) Pay the cost for any field test required by the board of
8 state canvassers.
9 (e) State the number of voters each component of the
10 electronic voting system can process per hour under each of the
11 following circumstances:
12 (i) An election in which there are 10 or fewer items to be
13 voted on the ballot by each voter.
14 (ii) An election in which the ballot consists of the number of
15 items typically voted on at a presidential general election in this
16 state.
17 (3) The board of state canvassers shall conduct a field test
18 of all new electronic voting systems as part of the certification
19 process. The field test shall must involve Michigan electors of
20 this state and election officials in simulated election day
21 conditions. The test shall must be designed to gauge voter reaction
22 to the electronic voting system, problems that voters have with the
23 electronic voting system, and the number of voting stations
24 required for the efficient operation of an election based upon the
25 vendor's statement provided under subsection (2)(e).
26 (4) The Subject to subsection (10), the board of state
27 canvassers shall approve an electronic voting system for use in
28 this state only if it that electronic voting system meets the
29 conditions of subsection (1) except that in an emergency situation
STM H02463'25 (H-1) m2t81w

7
1 that threatens the ability of a county, city, or township to
2 conduct a scheduled election, the board of state canvassers may
3 approve a correction of software or firmware after testing the
4 software or firmware performance.
5 (5) If an electronic voting system is approved for use before
6 January 1, 1997 by the board of state canvassers, it that
7 electronic voting system may be used in an election. However, if
8 the electronic voting system has its system's software or firmware
9 is improved or changed, the electronic voting system shall must
10 comply with the requirements of subsection (1).
11 (6) After an electronic voting system is approved, an
12 improvement or change in the electronic voting system shall must be
13 submitted to the board of state canvassers for approval pursuant to
14 under this section. This subsection does not apply to the technical
15 capability of a general purpose computer, reader, or printer to
16 electronically record and count votes.
17 (7) A county, city, township, village, or school district
18 shall file "an intent an "intent to purchase statement" with the
19 secretary of state 30 days before any purchase agreement is made to
20 purchase a new electronic voting system. The secretary of state
21 shall provide all information concerning the operation of the
22 electronic voting system in Michigan this state or any other state
23 to the local unit of government within 25 days after receiving the
24 "intent to purchase statement".
25 (8) The secretary of state shall instruct local election
26 officials regarding the operation and use of an approved electronic
27 voting system in order to carry out the purposes of sections 794 to
28 799a and the rules promulgated pursuant to under sections 794 to
29 799a.
